1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
In this lesson, we will look at how you can create a custom template, which lets you use a different design or layout from the rest of your website.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:12,000
This means you can create a page or post template with a unique header, footer or other page elements.

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:19,000
You might want to create a custom template for an event, a landing page, different types of blog posts or even have unique styles for different pages on your site.

4
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:30,000
To create a custom template, go to Appearance, click on Editor and then select Templates.

5
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:39,000
Let's first open the page template.

6
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:42,000
As you will notice, the page template already has a header and a footer.

7
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:49,000
And all pages assigned to this page template will have this header and footer.

8
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:55,000
But I want my contact page to have a different header and custom templates will help me achieve that.

9
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:02,000
So, let's make our way to Templates and then click on Add New Template.

10
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:10,000
And at the bottom, we can select Adding a Custom Template.

11
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:17,000
Give it a descriptive name and then click Create.

12
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:25,000
The Twenty Twenty-Four theme allows you to choose a template pattern or you can click on Skip to start with a blank template.

13
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:34,000
I'm going to go ahead and select the pattern as it will save me time.

14
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:40,000
As we can see, this is the same as my page template. We've got the header, the footer and the Post Content block in place.

15
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:50,000
But I would like my contact page to have a different header.

16
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:53,000
So, let's select the header, click on the three vertical dots and then select Replace.

17
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,000
And then I will add a new header to this template.

18
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:07,000
Now my new header is in place and the next step will be to save and then apply this template to my contact page.

19
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:16,000
So, once I've saved the template, I can return to the dashboard, go to Pages and then open up my contacts page.

20
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:27,000
At this stage, our contact page is still assigned to the pages template or the default template.

21
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:34,000
So, we are going to click on Swap Template as we want to assign a new template to this page.

22
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:40,000
And then we can choose the contact template which we have just created.

23
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:45,000
And now, the contact template has been assigned.

24
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:49,000
And once we've updated, we can make our way to the front end of the website.

25
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:54,000
We will see that our home page and other pages share this header.

26
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:58,000
But when we open our contact page, we will see that this page has its own unique header due to the fact that we have assigned a custom template to this page.

27
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:12,000
In the last example, I would like to create a custom template for a landing page that can be used for marketing purposes.

28
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:20,000
At the moment, I'm on the page that I've created for my landing page.

29
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:25,000
And if I open my sidebar settings, we will see this page is still assigned to the default page template.

30
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:32,000
And therefore, the landing page still has the same standard header and footer.

31
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:39,000
To create a custom template for this page, we are once again going to make our way to the Site Editor,

32
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:48,000
select Templates and then add a new template, and then select a custom template, and name it appropriately.

33
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:59,000
In this case, I will call it Drone Landing Page.

34
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:03,000
In this example, I'm not going to choose a template pattern, as I don't want a header or a footer on my landing page.

35
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,000
I want a more focused user experience. The aim of my landing page is to encourage the reader to click on the call to action.

36
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:19,000
So, I'm going to go ahead and click on Skip to start a template from scratch.

37
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:25,000
The only block I want to add is the Content Block, as that will pull in the content from the page.

38
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:31,000
I also want my landing page to be displayed in full width, so I will keep my content block as is.

39
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:38,000
Once I've saved the template, we can return to the dashboard.

40
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:42,000
Go to Pages and then open the landing page.

41
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:49,000
Next, we are going to assign the custom template to this page, namely the Drone Landing Page, which I've just created.

42
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:58,000
And once updated, we can click on Preview to see what our landing page will look like on the front end.

43
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,000
And of course, this landing page can be used on social media or in an email, for example.

44
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:11,000
I also wanted to mention that when you click on Templates and go to Manage All Templates, you will also be able to add a new template from here.

45
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:21,000
Happy creating! And remember, a custom template can be manually applied to any post or page.

